<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,150,717]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,367,393]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was placed as the basal branch sister to the clade (BP = 100) consisting of the remaining four species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[369,455,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis box="[369,455,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex (
<figureCitation box="[576,660,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1328,1352]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,181,1302]" captionTargetId="figure-22@18.[151,1436,181,1305]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. The strict consensus tree resulting from the parsimony analysis (PAUP* v4.0a168) of the data matrix of 25 spp. × 51 morphological characters (Appendix 6) for 20 species of the Colocasiomyia cristata group (as ingroup) and five species of the C. gigantea group (as outgroup). The tree is rooted by outgroup rooting, and synapomorphies (solid circle: nonhomoplastic; open circle: homoplastic) inferred from both ACCTRAN and DELTRAN character optimization are indicated on each internal branch along with support value (BP). Codes of clades (I and II) and subclades (IIa–c) are shown beside the corresponding branches (see the text for more explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766428/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
), lacking the following synapomorphies for the latter clade: anterior dorsocentral setae just beside transverse suture (ch.7-1), epandrium posteroventrally roundish (ch.30-1) and with setae thicker than cercal setae (ch.32-1), phallapodeme less sclerotized thin plate (ch.45-2) directed nearly perpendicular to axis of phallal sheath (ch.46-1), and hypoproct not pubescent (ch.48-1). In addition, within the latter clade, 
<taxonomicName box="[224,395,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sulawesiana">
<emphasis box="[224,395,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">C. sulawesiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda, 2021" authorityName="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda" authorityYear="2021" box="[409,581,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kinabaluana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[409,581,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">C. kinabaluana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[588,677,547,573]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[588,677,547,573]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda, 2021" authorityName="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda" authorityYear="2021" box="[731,840,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kotana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[731,840,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">C. kotana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[847,936,547,573]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[847,936,547,573]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
formed a clade (BP = 75; 
<figureCitation box="[1230,1310,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1328,1352]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,181,1302]" captionTargetId="figure-22@18.[151,1436,181,1305]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 13. The strict consensus tree resulting from the parsimony analysis (PAUP* v4.0a168) of the data matrix of 25 spp. × 51 morphological characters (Appendix 6) for 20 species of the Colocasiomyia cristata group (as ingroup) and five species of the C. gigantea group (as outgroup). The tree is rooted by outgroup rooting, and synapomorphies (solid circle: nonhomoplastic; open circle: homoplastic) inferred from both ACCTRAN and DELTRAN character optimization are indicated on each internal branch along with support value (BP). Codes of clades (I and II) and subclades (IIa–c) are shown beside the corresponding branches (see the text for more explanation)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766428/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) supported by an autapomorphy, the short (&lt;
<quantity box="[531,636,582,609]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
) processes on the male sternite VI (ch.25-1; 
<figureCitation box="[1153,1268,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male abdominal sternite VIs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (B in anteroventral view, C in lateral view), C. stamenicola (Carson &amp; Okada) (D in anterior view) and all species of the C. cristata subgroup (A in ventral view, E‒R in anterior view): A, C. ecornuta sp. nov.; E, C. grandis sp. nov.; F, C. vieti sp. nov.; G, C. cristata de Meijere; H, C. matthewsi sp. nov.; I, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso; J, C. kinabaluana sp. nov.; K, C. kotana sp. nov.; L, C. sabahana sp. nov.; M, C. sarawakana sp. nov.; N, C. pistilicola (Carson &amp; Okada); O, C. xenalocasiae (Okada); P, C. diconica (Toda &amp; Okada); Q, C. sumatrana sp. nov.; and R, C. leucocasiae sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766420/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Fig. 9I–K</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, 
<taxonomicName authority="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda, 2021" authorityName="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,298,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="matthewsi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,298,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">C. matthewsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[305,394,619,645]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[305,394,619,645]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
somewhat resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda, 2021" authorityName="Takano &amp; Gao &amp; Hu &amp; Li &amp; Yafuso &amp; Suwito &amp; Repin &amp; Pungga &amp; Meleng &amp; Kaliang &amp; Chong &amp; Toda" authorityYear="2021" box="[641,760,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[641,760,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">C. grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[767,856,619,645]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[767,856,619,645]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
in the morphology of periphallic organs (
<figureCitation box="[1324,1431,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1785,1809]" captionTargetBox="[242,1345,181,1761]" captionTargetId="figure-22@24.[242,1345,181,1761]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 16. Colocasiomyia ecornuta Toda &amp; Takano, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes and puparium from Soppeng, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Head (frontal view); B, scutum and scutellum (dorsal view); C, D, abdominal sternites in ventral view (C, male; D, female); E, periphallic organs (caudolateral view; inset: cercal ventral lobe); F, phallal sheath (dorsal view); G, H, phallic organs (G, lateral view; H, ventral view); I peri-oviscapt (caudal view); J, oviscapt (ventral view); K, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion at lower right and ventrolateral portion of segments at the upper right); L, mouth hook; M, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Abbreviations: i vt s, inner vertical setae; sctl, scutellum. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–J and M, 1.0 mm in K." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766438" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766438/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Figs 16D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,201,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="35.[151,250,1464,1488]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-18@35.[151,1435,181,1440]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURE 23. Colocasiomyia matthewsi Toda, sp. nov. (♂ and ♀ paratypes). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766452" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766452/files/figure.png" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">23C</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished from it by their diagnostic characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1376,691,717]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,150,717]" box="[199,1376,691,717]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
